It&#39;s because you did not initialise the Intger object. You wrote:

    Intger num1;
And only then in the for-loop did you assign an instance to the variable num1. Now, it cannot be guaranteed that the loop ever *gets* executed (even though it might seem obvious in this case), but it is assumed that loops may not execute, so in that case num1 would never have been initialised and you can&#39;t access fields of an object that does not exist.

If you instead wrote:

    Intger num1 = new Intger();
It would work and print 10 to the console like you expected it to.

By the way, your custom class `Intger` is irrelevant. You could just as well use the usual class, `Integer`, to see the same effects.

Also by the way, [`Object#finalize`][1] is now deprecated, and will eventually be removed. Best to avoid that method for several reasons. See [*JEP 421: Deprecate Finalization for Removal*][2].


----------

# &quot;may not have been initialized&quot; warning

As for you problems, both the [Comment by sorifiend][3] and the [Answer by Easy][4] are correct. 

&gt; it says the local variable may not have been initialized

This is a cautionary warning. Your IDE/compiler are mentioning that depending on conditions at runtime, the reference variable you define early on, and then use further down, may not have ever been assigned a value.

You may clear the warning by merely assigning `null`, as shown in the Comment. By assigning `null`, you make clear that you understand the value may continue to be null further down, later in the code. 

    Intger num1 = null ;  // Explicitly assign `null` to the reference variable.

# Null check

You could put a null-check in that later code. Change this:

    System.out.println( num1.num );

â€¦ to this:

